===Etymology===
English from the 17th century, from a {{etyl|ML.|en}} or {{etyl|NL.|en}} {{term|lexicon|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|λεξικόν||a lexicon|tr=lexicon|lang=grc}}, neuter of {{term|λεξικός||of words|tr=lexikos|lang=grc}}, from {{term|λέξις||a saying, speech, word|tr=lexis|lang=grc}}, from {{term|λέγειν||to speak|tr=legein|lang=grc}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|lĕ'ksĭkŏn}}, {{IPA|/ˈleksɪkɑn/}}
* {{audio|en-us-lexicon.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun|lexica|lexicons}}

# The [[vocabulary]] of a [[language]].
# {{context|linguistics|lang=en}} A [[dictionary]] that includes or focuses on [[lexeme]]s.
# A dictionary of Classical [[Greek]], [[Hebrew]], [[Latin]], or [[Aramaic]].
# {{context|programming|lang=en}} The [[lexicology]] of a [[programming language]]. (Usually called [[lexical structure]].)
# {{context|rare|lang=en}} Any dictionary.
# The [[vocabulary]] used by or [[know]]n to an individual. (Also called [[lexical knowledge]])
# A vocabulary specific to a certain subject.
#: ''a baseball '''lexicon'''''

